1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {We now focus on the Smyslov/Fianchetto Defense. In general, as you
will see, often White obtains a strong center. This is in large part due to
our next move, and the plan with it: c3 aiming for d4!} 4. c3 {There are 4
essential common tries for Black in this position:   (1) a6: The idea for
Black is to quickly ask our Bishop a question. What do we do? We put the
bishop on a4, which, as it turns out, does not change much. This will likely
lead to the same positions as in options (3) and (4), with little difference
for White. We can apply the same notions as in (3) and (4).   (2) d6: The idea
for Black is to defend e5, with later moves like Bg7 and Bd7 - which
indirectly defends e5 by freeing up the c6 knight. Black does not want to play
exd4 and give us the center in this line. What do we do? We eventually clarify
the situation by playing for d5!, and transform the pawn structure when it is
advantageous for us.   (3) Nge7 & playing for a quick d5: The idea for Black
is to quickly challenge our center, but it is unclear if this combination of a
quick center challenge goes well with the g6 pawn. What do we do? We trade on
e5, forcing the knight to come out. Then, at the right moment, we can take the
c6 knight, which is now undefended by the other knight, and claim some long
term strategic advantage.   (4) Perhaps the main move, at least in theory:
Black plays for Bg7 & Nge7, and tries to 0-0 quickly. The idea for Black is to
simply develop in the most harmonious way and get the King safe. What do we
do? We do not allow Black's king to sit safely on the Kingside, instead, we
push for the aggressive yet sound f4!} a6 {Option 1 & the most popular move} ( 4... d6 {Option 2: Black plays d6, and later Bd7 & Bg7 to keep the tension, so
as to not surrender us the entire center like in the a6 lines. But, we make
natural moves, until they either give us the center, or they are ready to
castle at which point we play d5! and transform the position into a Queenside
battle.} 5. d4 Bd7 6. O-O Bg7 7. Re1 Nge7 8. d5 Nb8 9. Bxd7+ Nxd7 10. Be3 O-O 11. c4 f5 ( 11... h6 12. Nfd2 c5 13. dxc6 bxc6 14. Nb3 Nf6 15. Nc3 Qc7 16. Qf3 Kh7 17. Red1 Rfd8 18. Rac1 a5 19. Na4 c5 20. Nc3 Nc6 21. Nd5 Nxd5 22. cxd5 Na7 23. Nxc5 $2 {The wrong decision. White would have enjoyed a slight advantage
after a4!} ( 23. a4 {[%cal Ge3d2,Gd2a5]} Rdb8 24. Nd2 Rxb2 25. Nc4 Rb3 26. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3d2,Rb3f3,Gd2a5]} ) 23... dxc5 24. Rxc5 Qb7 25. Rxa5 Nb5 26. Rxa8 Rxa8 27. a3 Nd4 28. Bxd4 exd4 29. b4 Rc8 30. Qf4 Qb5 31. h4 Qe2 32. Rd2 Qe1+ 33. Kh2 Re8 34. g3 Rxe4 35. Qf3 Qxd2 36. Qxe4 Qxf2+ 37. Kh1 Qf1+ 38. Kh2 d3 {0-1 (38)
Baghdasaryan,V (2388)-Bryzgalin,K (2485) Warsaw 2012} ) 12. Ng5 f4 13. Bd2 Rf6 14. Ne6 Rxe6 15. dxe6 Nf8 16. b4 Nxe6 17. Bc3 Qe8 18. Nd2 Qf7 19. Nf3 g5 20. h3 h5 21. c5 g4 22. hxg4 hxg4 23. Nh2 ) ( 4... Bg7 {We will look at Bg7 through
Nge7.} 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Nge7 ) ( 4... Nge7 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bg7 {Option 4!} ( 6... d5 {Option 3!} 7. exd5 {Again, our idea is to castle, and at some point
take on c6 to play against the doubled pawns.} Nxd5 8. O-O Bg7 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Bg5 Qd6 11. Re1+ Be6 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. Ne4 Qb4 14. Qc1 Rfe8 15. Bd2 Qb6 16. Nc5 Bf5 17. Ne5 Rad8 18. h3 Nf6 19. Nb3 Rd5 20. Nxc6 Rxe1+ 21. Bxe1 Bf8 22. Ne5 Be6 23. Nc4 Qb7 24. Ne3 Rh5 25. Nc5 Bxc5 26. dxc5 Bxh3 27. c6 Qc8 28. f3 Bxg2 29. Nxg2 Qh3 30. Bc3 Nd5 31. Bd4 f6 32. Qe1 Kf7 33. Rd1 Rg5 34. Qe2 Kg7 35. Bc5 Re5 36. Qf2 Rg5 37. Rd4 Qe6 38. Re4 Qxc6 39. Qd4 a5 40. a3 h5 41. Kh2 Kh7 42. Qc4 Qb7 43. Re7+ Kh8 44. Bd4 Rf5 45. Rd7 Qb8 46. Qc6 {1-0 (46) Naiditsch,A 
(2721)-Nakamura,H (2763) Douglas 2018} ) 7. d5 Ne5 8. Nxe5 Bxe5 9. O-O O-O ( 9... c6 10. f4 ) ( 9... a6 10. f4 ( 10. Ba4 {Or, we can even play this move
transposing to line (1)!.} ) ) 10. Nc3 a6 11. Ba4 b5 12. Bb3 d6 13. Bh6 Re8 14. f4 Bg7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qd4+ f6 17. h3 Bb7 18. Rad1 Nc8 19. Rde1 Qe7 20. a4 Nb6 21. Rf2 bxa4 22. Nxa4 Rab8 23. Nxb6 cxb6 24. Rfe2 b5 25. e5 Kf7 26. Re3 fxe5 27. fxe5 Rbc8 28. Qf4+ Kg8 29. exd6 Qf8 30. Qxf8+ Rxf8 31. Re7 Ba8 32. d7 Rcd8 33. d6+ Kh8 34. Re8 Bc6 35. Rxd8 Rxd8 36. Re8+ Rxe8 37. dxe8=Q+ Bxe8 38. Be6 Kg7 39. d7 Bxd7 40. Bxd7 Kf6 41. Kf2 Ke5 42. Bc8 a5 43. Bd7 b4 44. b3 Ke4 45. Kg3 Ke5 46. Kg4 Kf6 47. h4 Ke7 48. Bb5 Kf6 49. Kf4 Ke6 50. Ke4 Kd6 51. Kd4 Ke6 52. g4 Kd6 53. h5 g5 54. h6 Ke6 55. Bd3 Kf6 56. Bxh7 Kf7 57. Bd3 Kg8 58. Kc4 Kh8 59. Kb5 {1-0 (59) Gal,H (2074)-Furedi,E (1989) Budapest 2013} ) 5. Ba4 Nge7 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 d5 ( 7... Bg7 8. d5 Ne5 9. Nxe5 Bxe5 10. O-O {And again,
another pretty complete transposition.} ) 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. O-O Bg7 10. Bxc6+ {again we can opt for the same structural advantage as in option (3), the
position fully transposes, aside from the a6 pawn.} *